Canada Natural Gas Prices Soft On Low Demand, Uncertainty

09/13/2001
Dow Jones Energy Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

CALGARY -(Dow Jones)- A lack of fall's chill brought Canadian natural gas prices down Thursday on little demand and uncertainty about the New York Mercantile Exchange's reopening, traders said. 
At Alberta's benchmark AECO-C Hub day deals traded down to C$2.44-C$2.60 a gigajoule, falling 16 Canadian cents on the bid and 38 Canadian cents on the offer.
Prices were pushed down by a warming trend flowing into the province reducing demand, and the return of some 500 million cubic feet of gas volumes as plant turnarounds were completed, said traders. 
TransCanada's Alberta system pipeline linepack by mid-day was on target at 13.93 billion cubic feet. Field receipts were at 11.4 Bcf. 
Rest of month deals traded at C$2.62-C$2.65/GJ, with October deals averaging C$2.91-C$3/GJ, down 2 Canadian cents on the bid and 8 Canadian cents on the offer. 
The Nymex isn't expected to open until Monday, almost a week after terrorist attacks in New York shut the exchange. 
October natural gas futures swaps derivatives were trading around US$2.53-US$2.56 per million British thermal units on Enron Online and Intercontinental Exchange. 
At Station 2 in northern British Columbia day deals traded at C$2.65-C$2.72/GJ, falling 20 Canadian cents on the bid and 23 Canadian cents on the offer from Wednesday. 
Sumas deals, on the B.C.-Washington border, averaged US$1.82-US$1.85/MMBtu, dropping 15 US cents on the bid and 20 US cents on the offer. 
Malin deals on the Oregon-California border were the only ones to gain Thursday, advancing on tight pipes further down the line to US$2.58-US$2.61/MMBtu, up 43 US cents on the bid and 41 US cents on the offer. 
In Ontario, day deals were rangebound and soft, with Niagara trading at to US$2.55-US$2.58/MMBtu, or down 10 US cents on the bid and 14 US cents on the offer. 
Iroquois deals traded at US$2.58-US$2.61/MMBtu, gaining 3 US cents on the bid and losing 4 US cents on the offer. 
Trades at storage hub Dawn averaged US$2.50-US$2.62/MMBtu, falling 15 US cents. 
-By Dina O'Meara, Dow Jones Newswires; 403-531-2912; dina.omeara@dowjones.com

