US Physical Gas Prices Fall, Hold Well Below Oct

09/13/2001
Dow Jones Energy Service
(Copyright (c) 2001, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)

HOUSTON -(Dow Jones)- U.S. natural gas physical prices held in the $2.40s per million British thermal units Thursday as the market again struggled with a lack of liquidity and light demand, traders said. 
Cash prices held about 10 cents back from the October natural gas futures derivatives markets trading on Enron Online and the Intercontinental Exchange.
The futures swaps jumped as high as $2.56/MMBtu by late afternoon on fears of Tropical Storm Gabrielle in the Gulf of Mexico off Florida's coastline and lack of liquidity after Tuesday's apparent terrorist assault. 
There was no indication Thursday as to when the New York Mercantile Exchange or its efforts of Internet ACCESS trading would resume. Nymex was about to start evening Internet ACCESS when it was forced to evacuate its buildings. 
Some other financial markets announced they would reopen Monday. 
On Thursday, traders again came into the market only to level their positions and get out, according to several traders. Managers were on hand to keep traders from pushing the market, a trader said. 
At the benchmark Henry Hub in south Louisiana, the delivery point for Nymex gas, prices fell 4 cents-8 cents to a $2.33-$2.42/MMBtu closing range. 
First-of-month index for the Henry Hub is around $2.34/MMBtu. 
The October futures swaps contract, a Nymex "look-alike," rose about 9.5 cents to trade around $2.525-$2.535/MMBtu on electronic Enron Online and Intercontinental Exchange trading. 
Deals at Transcontinental Gas Pipe Line Station No. 65 were done at $2.33-$2.43/MMBtu, down about 7 cents-9 cents from Wednesday's closing range. 
At the Arizona-California Border, where gas from El Paso's pipeline begins delivery to Southern California, buyers paid $2.22-$2.35/MMBtu, down 5 cents-8 cents. Index is at $2.66/MMBtu. 
At PG&E Citygate, traders paid $2.17-$2.29/MMBtu, down 4 cents-7 cents. September first-of-month index is at $2.71/MMBtu. 
At the Katy hub in East Texas, prices were in a $2.26-$2.36/MMBtu range, down 6 cents-10 cents from its trading range on Wednesday. First-of-month September index is $2.37/MMBtu. 
At Waha in West Texas, buyers paid $2.18-$2.25/MMBtu, down 7 cents from its Wednesday range. Index is at $2.32/MMBtu, traders said. 
-By John Edmiston, Dow Jones Newswires; 713-547-9209; john.edmiston@dowjones.com

